[src:redux/api-eventtarget] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:redux/api-eventtarget] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:redux/api-eventtarget] The **`EventTarget`** interface is implemented by objects that can receive events and may have listeners for them.
[src:redux/api-eventtarget] In other words, any target of events implements the three methods associated with this interface.
[src:redux/api-eventtarget] `Element`, and its children, as well as `Document` and `Window`, are the most common event targets, but other objects can be event targets, too.
[src:redux/api-eventtarget] For example `IDBRequest`, `AudioNode`, and `AudioContext` are also event targets.
[src:redux/api-eventtarget] Many event targets (including elements, documents, and windows) also support registering event handlers via `onevent` properties and attributes.
[src:redux/api-eventtarget] Creates a new `EventTarget` object instance.
[src:redux/api-eventtarget] Registers an event handler of a specific event type on the `EventTarget`.
[src:redux/api-eventtarget] Removes an event listener from the `EventTarget`.
[src:redux/api-eventtarget] Dispatches an event to this `EventTarget`.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] In computing, **reactive programming** is a declarative programming paradigm concerned with data streams and the propagation of change.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] With this paradigm, it is possible to express static (e.g., arrays) or dynamic (e.g., event emitters) data streams with ease, and also communicate that an inferred dependency within the associated execution model exists, which facilitates the automatic propagation of the changed data flow.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] For example, in *imperative* programming, `a := b + c` would mean that `a` is being assigned the result of `b + c` at the time the expression is evaluated, and later, the values of `b` and `c` can be changed with no effect on the value of `a`.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] In contrast, in *reactive* programming, the value of `a` is automatically updated whenever the values of `b` or `c` change, without the program having to explicitly re-state the statement `a := b + c` to re-assign the value of `a`.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Another example is a hardware description language such as Verilog, where reactive programming enables changes to be modeled as they propagate through circuits.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has been proposed as a way to simplify creating interactive user interfaces and near-real-time computing animation.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] For example, in a model–view–controller (MVC) architecture, reactive programming can facilitate changes in an underlying *model* being reflected automatically in an associated *view*.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Several popular approaches are employed in creating reactive programming languages.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] One approach is the specification of *dedicated* languages that are specific to various *domain constraints*.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Such constraints usually are characterized by real-time, embedded computing or hardware description.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Another approach involves the specification of *general-purpose* languages that include support for reactivity.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Other approaches are articulated in the definition, and use of programming *libraries*, or *embedded domain-specific languages*, that enable reactivity alongside or atop a programming language.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Specification and use of these different approaches results in language *capability trade-offs*.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] In general, the more restricted a language is, the more its associated compilers and analysis programming tools are able to inform developers (e.g., in performing analysis for whether programs are able to execute in actual real-time).
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Functional trade-offs in specificity may result in deterioration of the general applicability of a language.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] A variety of models and semantics govern reactive programming.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Reactive programming language runtimes are represented by a graph that identifies the dependencies among the involved reactive values.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] In such a graph, *nodes* represent the act of computing, and *edges* model dependency relationships.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Such a runtime employs said graph, to help it keep track of the various computations, which must be executed anew, once an involved input changes value.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] At the implementation level, *event reaction* consists of the propagation across a graph's information, which characterizes the existence of change.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Consequently, computations that are affected by such change then become outdated and must be flagged for re-execution.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Such computations are then usually characterized by the transitive closure of the change (i.e., the full set of transitive dependencies a source affects) in its associated source.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] *Change propagation* may then lead to an update in the value of the graph's *sinks*.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Graph propagated information can consist of a node's complete state, i.e., the computation result of the involved node.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] In such cases, the node's previous output is then ignored.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Another method involves *delta propagation* i.e.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] In this case, information is proliferated along a graph's *edges,* which consist only of *delta*s describing how the previous node was changed.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] This approach is especially important when *nodes* hold large amounts of *state data*, which would otherwise be expensive to recompute from scratch.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Another common optimization is employment of *unary change accumulation* and *batch propagation*.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Such a solution can be faster because it reduces communication among involved nodes.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Optimization strategies can then be employed that reason about the nature of the changes contained within, and make alterations accordingly (e.g. two changes in the batch can cancel each other, and thus, simply be ignored).
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Yet another available approach, is described as *invalidity notification propagation*.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] This approach causes nodes with invalid input to pull updates, thus resulting in the update of their own outputs.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] A graph of dependencies is program-specific and generated by a programmer.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] When propagating changes, it is possible to pick propagation orders such that the value of an expression is not a natural consequence of the source program.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] We can illustrate this easily with an example.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Suppose `seconds` is a reactive value that changes every second to represent the current time (in seconds).
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Because `t` should always be greater than `seconds`, this expression should always evaluate to a true value.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Unfortunately, this can depend on the order of evaluation.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] When `seconds` changes, two expressions have to update: `seconds + 1` and the conditional.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] If the first evaluates before the second, then this invariant will hold.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] If, however, the conditional updates first, using the old value of `t` and the new value of `seconds`, then the expression will evaluate to a false value.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Some reactive languages are glitch-free and prove this property.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] This is usually achieved by topologically sorting expressions and updating values in topological order.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] This can, however, have performance implications, such as delaying the delivery of values (due to the order of propagation).
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Topological sorting of dependencies depends on the dependency graph being a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:redux/reactive-programming] In practice, a program may define a dependency graph that has cycles.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Usually, reactive programming languages expect such cycles to be "broken" by placing some element along a "back edge" to permit reactive updating to terminate.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Typically, languages provide an operator like `delay` that is used by the update mechanism for this purpose, since a `delay` implies that what follows must be evaluated in the "next time step" (allowing the current evaluation to terminate).
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Reactive languages typically assume that their expressions are purely functional.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] This allows an update mechanism to choose different orders in which to perform updates, and leave the specific order unspecified (thereby enabling optimizations).
[src:redux/reactive-programming] When a reactive language is embedded in a programming language with state, however, it may be possible for programmers to perform mutable operations.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] How to make this interaction smooth remains an open problem.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] In some cases, it is possible to have principled partial solutions.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] In some reactive languages, the graph of dependencies is *static*, i.e., the graph is fixed throughout a program's execution.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] In other languages, the graph can be *dynamic*, i.e., it can change as the program executes.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Every second, the value of this expression changes to a different reactive expression, which `t + 1` then depends on.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Therefore, the graph of dependencies updates every second.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Permitting dynamic updating of dependencies provides significant expressive power (for instance, dynamic dependencies routinely occur in graphical user interface (GUI) programs).
[src:redux/reactive-programming] However, the reactive update engine must decide whether to reconstruct expressions each time, or to keep an expression's node constructed but inactive; in the latter case, ensure that they do not participate in the computation when they are not supposed to be active.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Reactive programming languages can range from very explicit ones where data flows are set up by using arrows, to implicit where the data flows are derived from language constructs that look similar to those of imperative or functional programming.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] For example, in an implicitly lifted functional reactive programming (FRP), a function call might implicitly cause a node in a data flow graph to be constructed.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Reactive programming libraries for dynamic languages (such as the Lisp "Cells" and Python "Trellis" libraries) can construct a dependency graph from runtime analysis of the values read during a function's execution, allowing data flow specifications to be both implicit and dynamic.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Sometimes the term *reactive programming* refers to the architectural level of software engineering, where individual nodes in the data flow graph are ordinary programs that communicate with each other.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Reactive programming can be purely static where the data flows are set up statically, or be dynamic where the data flows can change during the execution of a program.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] The use of data switches in the data flow graph could to some extent make a static data flow graph appear as dynamic, and blur the distinction slightly.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] True dynamic reactive programming however could use imperative programming to reconstruct the data flow graph.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Reactive programming could be said to be of **higher order** if it supports the idea that data flows could be used to construct other data flows.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] That is, the resulting value out of a data flow is another data flow graph that is executed using the same evaluation model as the first.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Ideally all data changes are propagated instantly, but this cannot be assured in practice.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Instead, it might be necessary to give different parts of the data flow graph different evaluation priorities.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] This can be called **differentiated reactive programming**.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] For example, in a word processor, marking spelling errors need not be synchronized fully with adding or inserting characters.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Here, differentiated reactive programming can be used to give a spell checker lower priority, allowing it to be delayed while keeping other data flows more immediate.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] However, such differentiation introduces added design complexity.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] For example, deciding how to define the different data flow areas, and how to handle event passing between different data flow areas.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Evaluation of reactive programs is not necessarily based on how stack-based programming languages are evaluated.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Instead, when some data is changed, the change is propagated to all data that is derived partially or completely from the data that was changed.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] This change propagation could be achieved in a number of ways, where perhaps the most natural way is an invalidate/lazy-revalidate scheme.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] It could be problematic simply to naively propagate a change using a stack, because of potential exponential update complexity if the data structure has a certain shape.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] One such shape can be described as "repeated diamonds shape", and has the following structure: An→Bn→An+1, An→Cn→An+1, where n=1,2...
[src:redux/reactive-programming] This problem could be overcome by propagating invalidation only when some data is not already invalidated, and later re-validate the data when needed using lazy evaluation.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] One inherent problem for reactive programming is that most computations that would be evaluated and forgotten in a normal programming language, needs to be represented in the memory as data-structures.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] This could potentially make reactive programming highly memory consuming.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] However, research on what is called *lowering* could potentially overcome this problem.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] On the other side, reactive programming is a form of what could be described as "explicit parallelism", and could therefore be beneficial for using the power of parallel hardware.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has principal similarities with the observer pattern commonly used in object-oriented programming.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] However, integrating the data flow concepts into the programming language would make it easier to express them and could therefore increase the granularity of the data flow graph.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] For example, the observer pattern commonly describes data flows between whole objects/classes, whereas object-oriented reactive programming could target the members of objects/classes.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] It is possible to fuse reactive programming with ordinary imperative programming.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] In such a paradigm, imperative programs operate upon reactive data structures.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Such a set-up is analogous to imperative constraint programming; however, while imperative constraint programming manages bidirectional data-flow constraints, imperative reactive programming manages one-way data-flow constraints.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] One reference implementation is the proposed Quantum runtime extension to JavaScript.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Object-oriented reactive programming (OORP) is a combination of object-oriented programming and reactive programming.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Perhaps the most natural way to make such a combination is this: instead of methods and fields, objects have *reactions* that automatically re-evaluate when the other reactions they depend on have been modified.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] If an OORP language maintains its imperative methods, it would also fall under the category of imperative reactive programming.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Functional reactive programming (FRP) is a programming paradigm for reactive programming on functional programming.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] The actor model (actors) is proposed to design reactive systems, often combined with functional reactive programming (FRP) and Reactive Streams to develop distributed reactive systems.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] A newer category of programming languages uses constraints (rules) as main programming concept.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] It consists of reactions to events, which keep all constraints satisfied.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] Not only does this facilitate event-based reactions, but it makes reactive programs instrumental to the correctness of software.
[src:redux/reactive-programming] An example of a rule based reactive programming language is Ampersand, which is founded in relation algebra.
[src:redux/redux-javascript-library] Redux is a small library with a simple, limited API designed to be a predictable container for application state.
[src:redux/redux-javascript-library] It operates in a fashion similar to a reducing function, a functional programming concept.
[src:redux/redux-javascript-library] Redux was created by Dan Abramov and Andrew Clark in 2015.
[src:redux/redux-javascript-library] Abramov began writing the first Redux implementation while preparing for a conference talk at React Europe on hot reloading.
[src:redux/redux-javascript-library] Abramov remarks, "I was trying to make a proof of concept of Flux where I could change the logic.
[src:redux/redux-javascript-library] Abramov was struck by the similarity of the Flux pattern with a reducing function.
[src:redux/redux-javascript-library] "I was thinking about Flux as a reduce operation over time... your stores, they accumulate state in response to these actions.
[src:redux/redux-javascript-library] Abramov reached out to Andrew Clark (author of the Flux implementation Flummox) as a collaborator.
[src:redux/redux-javascript-library] Among other things, he credits Clark with making the Redux ecosystem of tools possible, helping to come up with a coherent API, implementing extension points such as middleware and store enhancers.
[src:redux/redux-javascript-library] By mid 2016, Abramov had joined the React team and passed the primary maintainership on to Mark Erikson and Tim Dorr.
[src:redux/redux-javascript-library] In February 2019, `useReducer` was introduced as a React hook in the 16.8 release.
[src:redux/redux-javascript-library] It provides an API that is consistent with Redux, enabling developers to create Redux-like stores that are local to component states.
[src:redux/redux-javascript-library] In October 2019, Redux Toolkit was introduced to simplify writing Redux logic by providing a set of utilities (such as `configureStore` and `createSlice`) that wrap and extend the standard Redux API.
[src:redux/state-management] This is especially the case when the state of any particular message or form on the page depends on factors outside of the current page, or available throughout several pages.
[src:redux/state-management] For example, consider a user who is logged in and sees the 'welcome' message on their first visit to any page, but not on subsequent page visits.
[src:redux/state-management] Does each page manage the state of the user being logged in?
[src:redux/state-management] That would create too much copy pasting and duplication of code.
[src:redux/state-management] Instead, you can use a state management pattern for handling messages (this may also include handling error messages and informative messages, along with the described welcome message) and then call this to receive a message as it becomes available.
[src:redux/state-management] Examples of state management libraries include Pinia as a state management library for the Vue.js JavaScript framework.
[src:redux/state-management] For the Angular framework there exist multiple community options: NgRx (based on Redux, with a lightweight alternative using Signals), NGXS and RxAngular.
[src:redux/state-management] Redux is a general-purpose state management library that can be used with any of the above frameworks or other view libraries, but is very commonly used with the React library.
[src:redux/state-management] As the documentation in Redux alludes, many of these state management libraries are lightweight and can be replaced by each other.
[src:redux/state-management] It's also possible to roll your own based on a publish–subscribe pattern where your interface components (like form fields, buttons, and messages) listen to a centralized data store in your application for new changes.
[src:redux/using-classes] JavaScript is a prototype-based language — an object's behaviors are specified by its own properties and its prototype's properties.
[src:redux/using-classes] However, with the addition of classes, the creation of hierarchies of objects and the inheritance of properties and their values are much more in line with other object-oriented languages such as Java.
[src:redux/using-classes] In this section, we will demonstrate how objects can be created from classes.
[src:redux/using-classes] In many other languages, *classes*, or constructors, are clearly distinguished from *objects*, or instances.
[src:redux/using-classes] In JavaScript, classes are mainly an abstraction over the existing prototypical inheritance mechanism — all patterns are convertible to prototype-based inheritance.
[src:redux/using-classes] Classes themselves are normal JavaScript values as well, and have their own prototype chains.
[src:redux/using-classes] In fact, most plain JavaScript functions can be used as constructors — you use the `new` operator with a constructor function to create a new object.
[src:redux/using-classes] We will be playing with the well-abstracted class model in this tutorial, and discuss what semantics classes offer.
[src:redux/using-classes] If you want to dive deep into the underlying prototype system, you can read the Inheritance and the prototype chain guide.
[src:redux/using-classes] This chapter assumes that you are already somewhat familiar with JavaScript and that you have used ordinary objects.
[src:redux/using-classes] If you have some hands-on experience with JavaScript, or have followed along with the guide, you probably have already used classes, even if you haven't created one.
[src:redux/using-classes] On the first line, we created an instance of the class `Date`, and called it `bigDay`.
[src:redux/using-classes] On the second line, we called a method `toLocaleDateString()` on the `bigDay` instance, which returns a string.
[src:redux/using-classes] Then, we compared two numbers: one returned from the `getTime()` method, the other directly called from the `Date` class *itself*, as `Date.now()`.
[src:redux/using-classes] `Date` is a built-in class of JavaScript.
[src:redux/using-classes] Classes are usually created with *class declarations*.
[src:redux/using-classes] Within a class body, there are a range of features available.
[src:redux/using-classes] If you came from a pre-ES6 world, you may be more familiar with using functions as constructors.
[src:redux/using-classes] After a class has been declared, you can create instances of it using the `new` operator.
[src:redux/using-classes] Typical function constructors can both be constructed with `new` and called without `new`.
[src:redux/using-classes] However, attempting to "call" a class without `new` will result in an error.
[src:redux/using-classes] Unlike function declarations, class declarations are not hoisted (or, in some interpretations, hoisted but with the temporal dead zone restriction), which means you cannot use a class before it is declared.
[src:redux/using-classes] This behavior is similar to variables declared with `let` and `const`.
[src:redux/using-classes] Similar to functions, class declarations also have their expression counterparts.
[src:redux/using-classes] Class expressions can have names as well.
[src:redux/using-classes] The expression's name is only visible to the class's body.
[src:redux/using-classes] Perhaps the most important job of a class is to act as a "factory" for objects.
[src:redux/using-classes] For example, when we use the `Date` constructor, we expect it to give a new object which represents the date data we passed in — which we can then manipulate with other methods the instance exposes.
[src:redux/using-classes] In classes, the instance creation is done by the constructor.
[src:redux/using-classes] As an example, we would create a class called `Color`, which represents a specific color.
[src:redux/using-classes] Users create colors through passing in an RGB triplet.
[src:redux/using-classes] You have successfully created a `Color` instance, and the instance has a `values` property, which is an array of the RGB values you passed in.
[src:redux/using-classes] Each time you call `new`, a different instance is created.
[src:redux/using-classes] Within a class constructor, the value of `this` points to the newly created instance.
[src:redux/using-classes] You can assign properties to it, or read existing properties (especially methods — which we will cover next).
[src:redux/using-classes] The `this` value will be automatically returned as the result of `new`.
[src:redux/using-classes] You are advised to not return any value from the constructor — because if you return a non-primitive value, it will become the value of the `new` expression, and the value of `this` is dropped.
[src:redux/using-classes] If a class only has a constructor, it is not much different from a `createX` factory function which just creates plain objects.
[src:redux/using-classes] However, the power of classes is that they can be used as "templates" which automatically assign methods to instances.
[src:redux/using-classes] For example, for `Date` instances, you can use a range of methods to get different information from a single date value, such as the year, month, day of the week, etc.
[src:redux/using-classes] You can also set those values through the `setX` counterparts like `setFullYear`.
[src:redux/using-classes] For our own `Color` class, we can add a method called `getRed` which returns the red value of the color.
[src:redux/using-classes] However, a problem is that this creates a new function every time a `Color` instance is created, even when they all do the same thing!
[src:redux/using-classes] In contrast, if you use a method, it will be shared between all instances.
[src:redux/using-classes] A function can be shared between all instances, but still have its behavior differ when different instances call it, because the value of `this` is different.
[src:redux/using-classes] If you are curious *where* this method is stored in — it's defined on the prototype of all instances, or `Color.prototype`, which is explained in more detail in Inheritance and the prototype chain.
[src:redux/using-classes] Similarly, we can create a new method called `setRed`, which sets the red value of the color.
[src:redux/using-classes] You might be wondering: why do we want to go to the trouble of using `getRed` and `setRed` methods, when we can directly access the `values` array on the instance?
[src:redux/using-classes] There is a philosophy in object-oriented programming called "encapsulation".
[src:redux/using-classes] This means you should not access the underlying implementation of an object, but instead use well-abstracted methods to interact with it.
[src:redux/using-classes] The user assumption that `values` means the RGB value suddenly collapses, and it may cause their logic to break.
[src:redux/using-classes] So, if you are an implementor of a class, you would want to hide the internal data structure of your instance from your user, both to keep the API clean and to prevent the user's code from breaking when you do some "harmless refactors".
[src:redux/using-classes] In classes, this is done through *private fields*.
[src:redux/using-classes] A private field is an identifier prefixed with `#` (the hash symbol).
[src:redux/using-classes] The hash is an integral part of the field's name, which means a private field can never have name clash with a public field or method.
[src:redux/using-classes] In order to refer to a private field anywhere in the class, you must *declare* it in the class body (you can't create a private element on the fly).
[src:redux/using-classes] Apart from this, a private field is pretty much equivalent to a normal property.
[src:redux/using-classes] Accessing private fields outside the class is an early syntax error.
[src:redux/using-classes] The language can guard against this because `#privateField` is a special syntax, so it can do some static analysis and find all usage of private fields before even evaluating the code.
[src:redux/using-classes] Private fields in JavaScript are *hard private*: if the class does not implement methods that expose these private fields, there's absolutely no mechanism to retrieve them from outside the class.
[src:redux/using-classes] This means you are safe to do any refactors to your class's private fields, as long as the behavior of exposed methods stay the same.
[src:redux/using-classes] After we've made the `values` field private, we can add some more logic in the `getRed` and `setRed` methods, instead of making them simple pass-through methods.
[src:redux/using-classes] If we leave the `values` property exposed, our users can easily circumvent that check by assigning to `values[0]` directly, and create invalid colors.
[src:redux/using-classes] But with a well-encapsulated API, we can make our code more robust and prevent logic errors downstream.
[src:redux/using-classes] A class method can read the private fields of other instances, as long as they belong to the same class.
[src:redux/using-classes] However, if `anotherColor` is not a Color instance, `#values` won't exist.
[src:redux/using-classes] (Even if another class has an identically named `#values` private field, it's not referring to the same thing and cannot be accessed here.) Accessing a nonexistent private element throws an error instead of returning `undefined` like normal properties do.
[src:redux/using-classes] If you don't know if a private field exists on an object and you wish to access it without using `try`/`catch` to handle the error, you can use the `in` operator.
[src:redux/using-classes] There are some limitations in using private elements: the same name can't be declared twice in a single class, and they can't be deleted.
[src:redux/using-classes] Methods, getters, and setters can be private as well.
[src:redux/using-classes] They're useful when you have something complex that the class needs to do internally but no other part of the code should be allowed to call.
[src:redux/using-classes] For example, imagine creating HTML custom elements that should do something somewhat complicated when clicked/tapped/otherwise activated.
[src:redux/using-classes] Furthermore, the somewhat complicated things that happen when the element is clicked should be restricted to this class, because no other part of the JavaScript will (or should) ever access it.
[src:redux/using-classes] In this case, pretty much every field and method is private to the class.
[src:redux/using-classes] Thus, it presents an interface to the rest of the code that's essentially just like a built-in HTML element.
[src:redux/using-classes] No other part of the program has the power to affect any of the internals of `Counter`.
[src:redux/using-classes] `color.getRed()` and `color.setRed()` allow us to read and write to the red value of a color.
[src:redux/using-classes] If you come from languages like Java, you will be very familiar with this pattern.
[src:redux/using-classes] However, using methods to simply access a property is still somewhat unergonomic in JavaScript.
[src:redux/using-classes] *Accessor fields* allow us to manipulate something as if it is an "actual property".
[src:redux/using-classes] It looks as if the object has a property called `red` — but actually, no such property exists on the instance!
[src:redux/using-classes] There are only two methods, but they are prefixed with `get` and `set`, which allows them to be manipulated as if they were properties.
[src:redux/using-classes] If a field only has a getter but no setter, it will be effectively read-only.
[src:redux/using-classes] In strict mode, the `red.red = 0` line will throw a type error: "Cannot set property red of #<Color> which has only a getter".
[src:redux/using-classes] In non-strict mode, the assignment is silently ignored.
[src:redux/using-classes] Private fields also have their public counterparts, which allow every instance to have a property.
[src:redux/using-classes] Fields are usually designed to be independent of the constructor's parameters.
[src:redux/using-classes] Public fields are almost equivalent to assigning a property to `this`.
[src:redux/using-classes] With the `Date` example, we have also encountered the `Date.now()` method, which returns the current date.
[src:redux/using-classes] This method does not belong to any date instance — it belongs to the class itself.
[src:redux/using-classes] However, it's put on the `Date` class instead of being exposed as a global `DateNow()` function, because it's mostly useful when dealing with date instances.
[src:redux/using-classes] Everything also has private counterparts.
[src:redux/using-classes] There is also a special construct called a *static initialization block*, which is a block of code that runs when the class is first loaded.
[src:redux/using-classes] Static initialization blocks are almost equivalent to immediately executing some code after a class has been declared.
[src:redux/using-classes] The only difference is that they have access to static private elements.
[src:redux/using-classes] A key feature that classes bring about (in addition to ergonomic encapsulation with private fields) is *inheritance*, which means one object can "borrow" a large part of another object's behaviors, while overriding or enhancing certain parts with its own logic.
[src:redux/using-classes] For example, suppose our `Color` class now needs to support transparency.
[src:redux/using-classes] However, this means every instance — even the vast majority which aren't transparent (those with an alpha value of 1) — will have to have the extra alpha value, which is not very elegant.
[src:redux/using-classes] Plus, if the features keep growing, our `Color` class will become very bloated and hard to maintain.
[src:redux/using-classes] Instead, in object-oriented programming, we would create a *derived class*.
[src:redux/using-classes] The derived class has access to all public properties of the parent class.
[src:redux/using-classes] In JavaScript, derived classes are declared with an `extends` clause, which indicates the class it extends from.
[src:redux/using-classes] There are a few things that have immediately come to attention.
[src:redux/using-classes] First is that in the constructor, we are calling `super(r, g, b)`.
[src:redux/using-classes] It is a language requirement to call `super()` before accessing `this`.
[src:redux/using-classes] The `super()` call calls the parent class's constructor to initialize `this` — here it's roughly equivalent to `this = new Color(r, g, b)`.
[src:redux/using-classes] You can have code before `super()`, but you cannot access `this` before `super()` — the language prevents you from accessing the uninitialized `this`.
[src:redux/using-classes] After the parent class is done with modifying `this`, the derived class can do its own logic.
[src:redux/using-classes] Here we added a private field called `#alpha`, and also provided a pair of getter/setters to interact with them.
[src:redux/using-classes] A derived class inherits all methods from its parent.
[src:redux/using-classes] Derived classes can also override methods from the parent class.
[src:redux/using-classes] For example, all classes implicitly inherit the `Object` class, which defines some basic methods like `toString()`.
[src:redux/using-classes] Within derived classes, you can access the parent class's methods by using `super`.
[src:redux/using-classes] This allows you to build enhancement methods and avoid code duplication.
[src:redux/using-classes] When you use `extends`, the static methods inherit from each other as well, so you can also override or enhance them.
[src:redux/using-classes] Derived classes don't have access to the parent class's private fields — this is another key aspect to JavaScript private fields being "hard private".
[src:redux/using-classes] Private fields are scoped to the class body itself and do not grant access to *any* outside code.
[src:redux/using-classes] This prevents problems in multiple inheritance like the diamond problem.
[src:redux/using-classes] However, due to the dynamic nature of JavaScript, it's still possible to achieve the effect of multiple inheritance through class composition and mixins.
[src:redux/using-classes] Instances of derived classes are also instances of the base class.
[src:redux/using-classes] The guide has been pragmatic so far: we are focusing on *how* classes can be used, but there's one question unanswered: *why* would one use a class?
[src:redux/using-classes] Classes introduce a *paradigm*, or a way to organize your code.
[src:redux/using-classes] Classes are the foundations of object-oriented programming, which is built on concepts like inheritance and polymorphism (especially *subtype polymorphism*).
[src:redux/using-classes] However, many people are philosophically against certain OOP practices and don't use classes as a result.
[src:redux/using-classes] For example, one thing that makes `Date` objects infamous is that they're *mutable*.
[src:redux/using-classes] Mutability and internal state are important aspects of object-oriented programming, but often make code hard to reason with — because any seemingly innocent operation may have unexpected side effects and change the behavior in other parts of the program.
[src:redux/using-classes] In order to reuse code, we usually resort to extending classes, which can create big hierarchies of inheritance patterns.
[src:redux/using-classes] However, it is often hard to describe inheritance cleanly when one class can only extend one other class.
[src:redux/using-classes] Often, we want the behavior of multiple classes.
[src:redux/using-classes] In Java, this is done through interfaces; in JavaScript, it can be done through mixins.
[src:redux/using-classes] But at the end of the day, it's still not very convenient.
[src:redux/using-classes] On the brighter side, classes are a very powerful way to organize our code on a higher level.
[src:redux/using-classes] But with classes, we can congregate them all under the `Color` namespace, which improves readability.
[src:redux/using-classes] In addition, the introduction of private fields allows us to hide certain data from downstream users, creating a clean API.
[src:redux/using-classes] In general, you should consider using classes when you want to create objects that store their own internal data and expose a lot of behavior.
[src:redux/using-classes] JavaScript offers the mechanism to organize your code in a canonical object-oriented way, but whether and how to use it is entirely up to the programmer's discretion.
